UML:TaggedValue.value: A borehole interval that fills the role of logElement SHALL have samplingFrame property value that is the borehole for which the interval is a logElement.

A borehole SHALL have exactly one reference location that is a geospatially located 3-D point that is the origin of the boring that created the hole. This point is the origin of a linear spatial reference system defined along the trace of the borehole.
A borehole is a kind of sampling curve, and SHALL inherit all properties and associations defined for GML v3.1 SF_SamplingCurve

A borehole may have associate drilling detail properties, including a drilling method category term, and a diameter property. Note that if a well is drilled with telescoped casing intervals with progressively smaller hole diameters, these would have to be represented as multiple boreholes...

A borehole SHALL have exactly one linear, 3-D trace (shape) located within the Earth; this trace SHALL be represented in at least one of the following three ways: 1. a GML GML_Object that represents a Curve 2. a bearing and plunge from the well bore origin, approximating the well bore as a straight, inclined Curve 3. implicitly as a vertical line extending downward from the well bore origin
A mappedInterval is a kind of MappedFeature and inherits the following properties: observationMethod, specification (mandatory), and positionalAccuracy, resolutionScale (voidable)

A borehole MAY have an associated borehole details property collection. Properties in the collection are all voidable, and include: operator--person or organization responsible for the borehole driller--person or organization responsible for drilling the borehole date of drilling--the time period between when drilling started and total depth was reached. start Point--category indicating the position relative to ground surface of the borehole origin. inclination Type--category qualitatively indicating the orientation of the borehole relative to the Earth Surface. borehole Material Custodian--person or organization who is responsible for curating sample materials obtained from the borehole purpose--category that specifies why the borehole was drilled data Custodian--person or organization who is responsible for curating data obtained from the borehole borehole Length--numeric quantity specifying the length of the well bore.
A borehole MAY have one or more associated mapped intervals
A Borehole is a kind of GML Feature and SHALL inherit all the properties and associations of GML Feature.

A PlanarOrientationProperties instance is a kind of GeometricDescriptionValue, and SHALL inherit the properties from that class; A PlanarOrientationProperties instance SHALL have a convention property that is a category value specifying the manner in which the orientation value is specified A PlanarOrientationProperties instance MAY have additional properties for azimuth and dip that are numeric range values, and a polarity property that is a code value indicating whether the planar orientation is associated with a directed feature that is overturned, upright, vertical etc. At least one of polarity, azimuth, or dip SHALL have a value that is not nil.

A GeometricDescriptionValue MAY have two properties: determinationMethod: a category that specifies how the orientation value was determined. descriptiveOrientation: a qualitative text specification of the orientation
A quantityRange value SHALL inherit all Properties and requirements from SWE QuantityRange.
A Vector quantity is a kind of LinearOrientation and SHALL inherit all properties from that class, and SHALL have a magnitude property that is specified as a QuantityRange value.

A GSML element is a kind of GML Feature and SHALL inherit all properties and requirements from that class. A GSML instance SHALL have an association to at least one member that is a GSMLItem A GSML instance MAY have one associated Metadata record that describes the collection.
A GSML collection member SHALL an instance of one of the following classes: EarthMaterial, GeologicFeature, GML geometry object, MappedFeature, GeologicRelation, or SamplingFeature.
An EarthMaterial instance SHALL have a purpose property that is from the set of categories {definingNorm, instance, typicalNorm}
An EarthMaterial description instance SHALL have a geochemistry property specified either by a ChemicalComposition entity, or by a nil value.
A geologic feature may be associated with a metadata record that provides information about the provenance of the feature
A mapped feature SHALL have a geospatial location

A geologic feature instance represents either a feature instance, a normative feature description that characterizes a feature type, or a typical feature description that characterizes a collection of feature instances.
A mapped feature may be associated with a metadata record that provides information about the provenance of the feature
If the purpose of a geologic feature is 'instance', then it SHALL have at least one Mapped Feature occurrence
A geologic feature instance is the result of one or more observations, and as such has an observation method property that categorizes the method used to characterize the feature properties.
A geologic feature may have one or more associated classifier concepts that categorize the feature.
A geologic feature is a kind of feature and inherits GML abstract feature properties: name, description, bounding box, metadata

The resolution of the geospatial location of a mapped feature SHALL BE quantified by a spatial resolution property. The spatial resolution is related to the smallest distance between points on the mapped feature trace that can be distinguished in the database representation of the feature. This is in contrast to position accuracy which is a measure of how well a feature is located relative to other features in the geographic reference system.
A mapped feature can be marked as concealed or exposed
A mapped feature is a kind of feature and inherits the properties of abstract GML feature
A geologic feature may have 1 or more mapped features that represent occurrences of the geologic feature
The uncertainty in the geospatial positioning of a mapped feature is expressed by a positional accuracy property.
A mapped feature SHALL BE associated with exactly one geologic feature that represents the geologic entity located by the mapped feature.

A mapped feature has a property that categorizes the sampling frame within which the mapped trace is located by the feature. Discussion: This enables mapping from a single coordinate pair (when the sampling feature is a 3-D line) or planar 2-D point, line or polygon (when the sampling feature is a surface) to a true 3-D trace.
A mapped feature instance is the result of one or more observations, and as such has an observation method property that categorizes the method used to characterize the feature properties.
A geologic feature relation is a kind of geologic relation for which the source and target classes SHALL BE geologic feature instances.
An EarthMaterialRelation is a GeologicRelation in which the source and target entities SHALL be instances of ConstituentPart

A GeologicRelation SHALL be categorized by a relationship category term A GeologicRelation instance SHALL have an association to an entity that plays the source role in the relationship A GeologicRelation instance SHALL have associations to one or more entities that play the target role in the relationship. A GeologicRelation may have roles of the source and target entities specified by one source and one target role category terms.
